    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b121b23eb90bc60f",
      "text": "Examine, e.g., the politics of society with the criteria that we normally reserve for societal operating systems, such as functional systems. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ce5f85b59b2cf301",
      "text": "There is basically only one assumption which we have to cross out if we intend such an examination, namely the assumption that the operations of a system have to be connected with all of them, as it were, realizing a kind of complete connexity in which it could be shown how each operation produces a next operation in the network of the same operations. But one could instead say that it is only a matter of which operations are attributed [→[[Attribution (Zurechnung)]]] to the network and which are not, i.e. how the system distinguishes what is its 'inside', what is its 'outside', and what thus realizes the 'network'. For example, one cannot well say that every thought of a consciousness is related to every other one of the same consciousness, but very well that a consciousness distinguishes between 'its' thoughts and those thought in the elsewhere of other mental systems."
